9️⃣ Harsh Realities of IIT M.Tech (Students Wish They Knew)
Reality 1: M.Tech Core Placements Are Unpredictable

Example:

Ocean engineering student with 8.5+ CGPA got only 7 LPA.

Some get 10 interview calls, but convert only the lowest package.

Some get only 1 interview but that gives 20+ LPA.

Luck + timing matter in placements.

Reality 2: Don’t Blindly Accept On-Campus Offers

Two stories:

Tier-3 student called the creator begging for help.
Needed off-campus referrals.

An IIT student:

Got 75 LPA on-campus

Rejected it

Used alumni referral to get better package in Hong Kong

Lesson: On-campus is not the only path. Networking matters.

Reality 3: M.Tech Without GATE Is Possible

A student:

Became a project associate under IIT professor.

Completed two IIT courses with good grades.

Got converted into M.Tech — no GATE, no high CGPA.

But there are challenges:

Professors expect:

One journal paper

High-quality output

CGPA is hard because:

12 subjects

Relative grading

Competing with GATE toppers

CGPA affects:

Placements

Stipend continuation

Research opportunities

Reality 4: Stipend Problem

M.Tech stipend has not changed for 10+ years.

Meanwhile:

Fees increased (e.g., IITM: 61k → 65k)

Hostel costs ≈ 40k per semester

Many students struggle financially and take loans.

10️⃣ The Final Message

IIT opens unique opportunities unavailable elsewhere.

But:

It demands continuous hard work

You must keep upgrading

You must build contact and involve in activities

Otherwise:

People may doubt your ability

Companies may fire you (as in the opening story)

Power of IIT tag exists only if you keep growing after getting in.

11️⃣ Takeaway on Consistency

63% of students fail due to lack of consistency, not lack of intelligence.

The creator promotes a video where he teaches psychological methods to build a daily routine.

⭐ ONE-LINE SUMMARY

IIT gives massive advantages—placements, promotions, foreign opportunities, professor influence—but the benefits require awareness, consistent skill upgrade, smart professor choice, and financial planning. The IIT tag alone is not enough; continuous growth is mandatory.
